It’s a great local pizza shop with some film history in one of those 80s Travolta flicks. The grandma pie is divine and most of the other pizzas are good. The staff is attentive and hard working. There’s better pizza in Brooklyn, but it’s still pretty good. Only downside is that the salads are typical pizza shop slop, and the dessert menu is just one cheap item: mini italian donut balls. You don’t want more generic carbs after pizza: at least sell some Italian pastries or something.

We booked a month ahead and arrived at the restaurant at almost 5pm on a tuesday, a lil earlier than our reservation, anyways they let us in with a smile and a table ready for us in a minute. The waiter took quite long to come get our order and refill water, but overall the service wasn't too bad. The food, on the other hand, was spectacular. We had the Finnochiona pizza which is made of salame, mozzarella, and tomato. It was really good! The crust was perfect and the sauce was great too. Even my mom, who normally is not much of a pizza fan, loved it! The price is not too expensive(or at least in our opinions) for this type of restaurant. We'd totally go back to Lenny's Pizza the next time we go to NY.

In a neighborhood where pizza competition is tough, Lennys is one of my favorite spots for a “Grandma slice.” It’s the first place I ate a grandma slice and a place I always try to visit when I have my craving for a good grandma slice. The regular slice is ok too and they have other options like wheels and Stromboli’s but I think the grandma’s slice stands out the most among everybody else.  The reason I give it 4 stars and not 5 is because I think the regular slice is 3.5 but the grandma Slice is a 5.  Lennys was made popular because of John Travolta and Saturday night fever but I’m not into the trend of getting 2 regular slices and folding them up.  Get the grandma slice here

This is my go to and it's great for poker nights because the guys still want to play after eating it, it doesn't leave you feeling weighed down.
